2856      """* 
2857      * By default, this property is <tt>False</tt>, which means 
2858      * that GChart will retain no-longer-needed Image and Grid 
2859      * widgets (plus any user object references associated with 
2860      * those widgets, such as those created via the 
2861      * <tt>setAnnotationText</tt> and 
2862      * <tt>setAnnotationWidget</tt> methods) between 
2863      * <tt>updates</tt> in the expectation that they may be 
2864      * needed by future updates.  This strategy often makes 
2865      * updates faster, because building Image and Grid 
2866      * elements "from scratch" is very expensive.  However, 
2867      * strictly speaking, GChart is holding onto memory it no 
2868      * longer needs to render the chart <i>right now</i>--which 
2869      * would normally be considered a memory leak if it were not 
2870      * being done deliberately.  <p> 
2871      * 
2872      * If <tt>optimizeForMemory</tt> is set to <tt>True</tt>, 
2873      * GChart will (at the very next <tt>update()</tt> call) free 
2874      * up any Image or Grid elements that are no longer required 
2875      * to render the current chart.  Should a chart's size grow back 
2876      * to a former size, the subsequent update would be slower, 
2877      * though. 
2878      * 
2879      * <p> Charts that use exactly the same number of Image and 
2880      * Grid elements for each update (for example a bar chart 
2881      * where the number of bars is fixed) will see no impact on 
2882      * either memory use or update speeds by setting this 
2883      * parameter.  Charts that have a highly variable number of 
2884      * Image or Grid elements (for example, a chart whose number 
2885      * of points varies randomly between 5 and 500) may see a 
2886      * very large impact on speed (False is faster) or memory 
2887      * (True is more compact). 
2888      * <p> 
2889      * 
2890      * The setting of this parameter never has any impact on the 
2891      * speed or memory used on the <i>very first</i> chart 
2892      * update. 
2893      * <p> 
2894      * 
2895      * In one test using the future oil price simulation chart of 
2896      * GChart's live demo (which has only small changes in the 
2897      * number of elements required to render the chart between 
2898      * updates) setting this parameter to True made the updates, 
2899      * on average, around 10% slower, but also reduced the memory 
2900      * footprint by around 2%. 
2901      * 
2902      * @param optimizeForMemory <tt>True</tt> to optimize updates 
2903      * to use less memory, <tt>False</tt> (the default) to 
2904      * optimize them to use less time. 
2905      * 
2906      * @see #update update
